  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "LLFHzcick2B8BUT/BXCADKHrKR4=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:29.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "## Decision\n\nConnect's chat/collab stack uses two complementary Swarm protocols, each selected for the traffic it serves:\n\n| Feature | Protocol | Why |\n|---|---|---|\n| Chat messages | **PSS** | End-to-end encrypted, 1-to-1, async delivery acceptable |\n| Typing indicators | **GSOC** | Low latency (<1s), ephemeral |\n| Document share notification | **GSOC** | Instant ping when share bundle is ready |\n| Live collaboration signals | **GSOC** | Sub-second cursor/op-committed |\n| Operation sync | **Feeds + GSOC notify** | Persistent ops via feeds, GSOC triggers pull |\n\n## Rationale\n\n- PSS gives per-message asymmetric encryption for free but costs 2\u201310s of Trojan mining. That's fine for a chat message, fatal for a typing hint.\n- GSOC mines the signer once (~10\u201330s) and then every subsequent send is a normal SOC update \u2014 milliseconds of latency, symmetric encryption via the shared signer.\n- The two protocols compose: PSS carries the message, GSOC pings the recipient's UI to render it immediately instead of waiting for the next PSS poll.\n\n## Consequence\n\nTyping indicators were designed on top of GSOC but ultimately scratched. The GSOC plumbing survives and is being reused for live collaboration.",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:29.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:29.000Z"
    }
  },
